The paper deals with information channels, their properties, and their comparison. This falls under the domain of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses information decompositions, which is a topic in information theory and probability (cs.ITP). The comparison of channels involves expected utility and mutual information, which are concepts in machine learning and statistics (cs.LG). The paper also involves the construction and manipulation of channels, which can be seen as a problem in data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the contradiction of the intuition that coarse-graining can only destroy information, which is a topic in social and information networks (cs.SI).
